    <h1>Other Antihypertensives (ACE Inhibitors & ARBs)</h1>
    
    <p>Overdoses of ACE inhibitors (e.g., lisinopril) or Angiotensin II Receptor Blockers (e.g., losartan) generally cause profound vasodilation and hypotension. Bradycardia is usually absent (unlike CCB/Beta Blocker toxicity) unless there is reflex tachycardia or concomitant medications.</p>

    <h2>Weight-Based Resuscitation & Management</h2>

    <div class="calc-box">
        <h3>1. IV Fluid Resuscitation</h3>
        <p>First-line therapy to fill the expanded vascular space.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Dose:</strong> 20 mL/kg Isotonic Crystalloid IV bolus. Repeat as necessary.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="calc-box">
        <h3>2. Vasopressors</h3>
        <p>If unresponsive to IV fluids.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Norepinephrine:</strong> 0.05 - 0.1 mcg/kg/min IV. Often the preferred first-line pressor.</li>
            <li><strong>Epinephrine:</strong> 0.05 - 0.1 mcg/kg/min IV.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="calc-box">
        <h3>3. Specific Therapies (Refractory Cases)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Angiotensin II (Giapreza):</strong> If available, directly targets the disrupted pathway. Start at 20 ng/kg/min IV.</li>
            <li><strong>Naloxone:</strong> Case reports suggest 0.4 - 2 mg IV may help reverse profound ACEi-induced hypotension by antagonizing endogenous opioids released during shock, though not universally proven.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
